problem:
Determine the number of integers $x$ such that $0\le x< 12$ and $x$ satisfies the following system of equations: \begin{align*}
&x-1\equiv 1-x\pmod {12},\\
&x-2\equiv 2-x\pmod{12}.
\end{align*}

model_solution:
We can rewrite the system of equations as \begin{align*}
&x-1\equiv 1-x\pmod {12},\\
&x-2\equiv 2-x\pmod{12}.
\end{align*}
Adding the two equations together, we get $2x-3\equiv 3-x\pmod{12}$, which simplifies to $3x\equiv 6\pmod{12}$. Dividing both sides by 3, we have $x\equiv 2\pmod{12}$. This congruence has exactly one solution modulo 12, which is $x=2$. Therefore, there is only one integer $x$ that satisfies the system of equations. The number of integers $x$ is $\boxed{1}$. The answer is: 1.

